1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:05,387
(Luke 2:19): ‘I must be about my Father’s business.

2
00:00:05,337 --> 00:00:16,837
This text is opportune to what we have to say concerning the eternal birth which took place here in time and is still happening daily in the innermost recesses of the soul, in her ground, remote from all comers.

3
00:00:16,837 --> 00:00:22,837
To become aware of this interior birth it is above all necessary to be about our Father’s business.

4
00:00:22,837 --> 00:00:25,212
What is peculiarly the Father’s?

5
00:00:25,212 --> 00:00:29,212
Power is ascribed to him beyond either of the other Persons.

6
00:00:29,212 --> 00:00:33,887
And I tell you, no one can experience this birth without a mighty effort.

7
00:00:33,887 --> 00:00:38,800
None can attain this birth unless he can withdraw his mind entirely from things.

8
00:00:38,800 --> 00:00:43,387
And it requires main force to drive back all the senses and inhibit them.

9
00:00:43,387 --> 00:00:47,550
Violence must be offered to them one and all or this cannot be done.

10
00:00:47,550 --> 00:00:53,125
As Christ said: ‘The kingdom of heaven suffereth violence and the violent take it by force.

11
00:00:53,125 --> 00:01:05,600
Regarding this birth there arises the question, Does it happen continuously or only at intervals when one is disposed for it, what time one is exerting oneself to the utmost to forget things altogether and be conscious in this?

12
00:01:05,600 --> 00:01:07,612
Here let us discriminate.

13
00:01:07,612 --> 00:01:12,837
Man possesses an active intellect, a passive intellect and a potential intellect.

14
00:01:12,837 --> 00:01:20,250
Active intellect is ever in act, ever doing something, be it in God or in creature, to the honour and glory of God.

15
00:01:20,250 --> 00:01:23,412
That is its province and hence its name active.

16
00:01:23,412 --> 00:01:28,200
But when God undertakes the work the mind must preserve a state of passivity.

17
00:01:28,200 --> 00:01:35,725
Potential intellect again has regard to both these, to the action of God and the passion of the soul, to its acting potentially.

18
00:01:35,725 --> 00:01:46,987
In the one case the mind is active, when it is functioning, to wit; in the other receptive, when God takes up the work and then the mind ought, nay must, remain still and allow God to act.

19
00:01:46,987 --> 00:01:54,362
Now ere this is begun by the mind and finished by God, the spirit has prevision of it, potential knowledge of its happening.

20
00:01:54,362 --> 00:02:00,975
This is the meaning of potential intellect, which, however, is often neglected and does not bear fruit.

21
00:02:00,975 --> 00:02:09,487
When the mind is exerting itself in real earnest, God interests himself in the mind and its work, and then the soul sees and experiences God.

22
00:02:09,487 --> 00:02:22,700
But since the uninterrupted vision and passion of God is intolerable to the soul in this body, therefore God withdraws from the soul from time to time, as it is said, ‘A little while ye see me, and again a little while and ye do not see me.

23
00:02:22,700 --> 00:02:36,637
When our Lord took his three disciples with him up the mountain and showed them the transfiguration of his body by union with the Godhead, which also we shall have in our archetypal body, straightway Peter, beholding it, was fain to remain there always.

24
00:02:36,637 --> 00:02:41,712
Verily, where we find good we are loath to leave it, in so far as it is good.

25
00:02:41,712 --> 00:02:46,812
Where intuition finds, love follows and memory and all the soul to boot.

26
00:02:46,812 --> 00:02:55,412
And our Lord knowing this hides himself sometimes; for the soul is the impartible form of the body, so she turns as a whole to whatever she turns.

27
00:02:55,412 --> 00:03:03,200
Were she conscious of good, God to wit, immediately, uninterruptedly, she would never be able to leave it to influence the body.

28
00:03:03,200 --> 00:03:11,787
Thus it befell Paul: had he remained a hundred years there, where he knew the good, he would never have returned to his body, he would have forgotten it completely.

29
00:03:11,787 --> 00:03:24,700
Seeing then that it is wholly foreign to this life, and incompatible therewith, the good God veils it when he will and unveils it again when he chooses and when he knows, like a trusty physician, that it is best and most useful for thee.

30
00:03:24,700 --> 00:03:32,425
This withdrawal is not thine, but his whose is also the work; let him do it or not as he will, he knows what is good for thee.

31
00:03:32,425 --> 00:03:37,250
It is in his hands to show or not according as he knows thee able to endure it.

32
00:03:37,250 --> 00:03:44,087
God is not a destroyer of nature, he perfects it, and this God does ever more and more as thou art fitted for it.

33
00:03:44,236 --> 00:03:53,811
When a man is quite idle, when his intellect is at rest within him, then God takes up the work: he himself is the agent who produces himself in the passive intellect.

34
00:03:44,236 --> 00:04:03,311
Haply thou wilt object: Alas, Sir, if this requires a mind quite free from images and without activity, albeit both are natural to its powers, then how about those outward works we must do sometimes, works of charity, external ones, such as teaching and comforting those in need thereof: are we debarred by these?

35
00:03:53,761 --> 00:03:55,648
What happens is this.

36
00:03:55,648 --> 00:04:02,873
The active intellect cannot give what it has not got: it cannot have two ideas together, but first one and then the other.

37
00:04:02,873 --> 00:04:09,798
What though light and air show multitudes of forms and colours all at once, thou canst only observe them one after another.

38
00:04:03,311 --> 00:04:14,536
things which so occupied our Lord’s disciples, notably St Paul, who endured a father’s care on account of other people: are we to be deprived of this great good because we are engaged in charities?

39
00:04:09,798 --> 00:04:13,711
And so with thy active intellect, which resembles the eye.

40
00:04:13,711 --> 00:04:19,948
But when God acts in lieu of thy active intellect he engenders many images together in one point.

41
00:04:14,536 --> 00:04:16,286
The answer is this.

42
00:04:16,286 --> 00:04:19,636
The one is perfect, the other very profitable.

43
00:04:19,636 --> 00:04:26,561
Mary was praised for choosing the best, but Martha’s life was very useful, serving Christ and his disciples.

44
00:04:19,948 --> 00:04:28,636
Suppose God prompts thee to some one good deed, thy powers are all proffered for all virtuous things, thy mind being straightway set on good in general.

45
00:04:26,561 --> 00:04:35,448
St Thomas says the active life is better than the life of contemplation, so far as we actually spend in charity the income we derive from contemplation.

46
00:04:28,636 --> 00:04:34,911
All thy possibilities for good take shape and come into thy mind collectively, focussed to one point.

47
00:04:34,911 --> 00:04:45,161
Clearly this is not the work of thine own intellect which has in no wise the perfection nor plenitude for it; rather is it the work and product of him who has all forms at once in himself.

48
00:04:35,448 --> 00:04:44,836
It is all the same thing; we have but to root ourselves in this same ground of contemplation to make it fruitful in works, and the object of contemplation is achieved.

49
00:04:44,836 --> 00:04:51,423
True, there is motion, but no more than one; it comes from one end, God, and goes back to the same.

50
00:04:45,161 --> 00:04:51,023
As Paul says: ‘I can do all things in him who strengtheneth me; in him I am undivided.

51
00:04:51,023 --> 00:04:59,098
Know then, the ideas of these acts are not thine own: they belong to the author of thy nature who has planted therein both their energy and form.

52
00:04:51,423 --> 00:04:57,761
As though I went from one end to the other of this house; that would in sooth be motion, but of one in the same.

53
00:04:57,761 --> 00:05:02,548
Even so in this activity we are in the state of contemplation in God.

54
00:04:59,098 --> 00:05:02,498
Lay no claim thereto, for it is his not thine.

55
00:05:02,498 --> 00:05:09,673
True, thou receivest it temporally, but it is gotten and born of God beyond time, in eternity above images.

56
00:05:02,548 --> 00:05:05,748
The one is centred in the other and perfects the other.

57
00:05:05,748 --> 00:05:14,661
God’s purpose in the union of contemplation is fruitfulness in works; for in contemplation thou servest thyself alone, but the many in good works.

58
00:05:09,673 --> 00:05:19,611
Thou wilt say, perhaps: From the moment my intellect is divested of its natural activity and no longer has either form or action of its own, what is preserving it?

59
00:05:14,661 --> 00:05:23,286
Hereto Christ admonisheth us by his whole life and the lives of all his saints, every one of whom he drove forth into the world to teach the multitude.

60
00:05:19,611 --> 00:05:28,161
It must have a hold somewhere; the powers, whether memory, intellect or will, are bound to have some lodgment somewhere, some place to work in.

61
00:05:23,286 --> 00:05:27,373
St Paul said to Timothy, ‘Beloved, preach the Word.

62
00:05:27,373 --> 00:05:30,411
Did he mean the outward word that beats the air?

63
00:05:28,161 --> 00:05:29,961
The answer is this.

64
00:05:29,961 --> 00:05:36,861
Intellect’s object and sustenance is essence, not accident, just pure unadulterated being in itself.

65
00:05:30,411 --> 00:05:31,948
Nay, surely!

66
00:05:31,948 --> 00:05:44,298
He meant the in-born, hidden Word that lies secreted in the soul; it was this that he exhorted them to preach, to the end that it might be made known to and nourish the powers of such as spend themselves wholly in the exterior life.

67
00:05:36,861 --> 00:05:46,011
On descrying something real the intellect forthwith relies upon it, comes to rest thereon, pronouncing its intellectual word concerning the object attained.

68
00:05:44,298 --> 00:05:50,511
That what time thy fellow-man hath need of thee thou mayst be found ready to serve him to the best of thy ability.

69
00:05:46,011 --> 00:06:01,098
As long as intellect fails to find the actual truth of things, does not touch bedrock in them, it stays in a condition of quest and expectation, it never settles down to rest, but labours incessantly to trace things to their cause, that is, it is seeking and waiting.

70
00:05:50,511 --> 00:05:56,298
It must be within thee, in thought, in intellect and will, and shine forth in thy deeds.

71
00:05:56,298 --> 00:05:59,723
As Christ said, ‘Let your light shine before men.

72
00:05:59,723 --> 00:06:09,761
He was thinking of those people who care only for the contemplative life and neglect the virtuous uses of it, which, they say, do not concern them, they are passed that stage.

73
00:06:01,098 --> 00:06:09,936
It spends perhaps a year or more in research on some natural fact, finding out what it is, only to work as long again stripping off what it is not.

74
00:06:09,761 --> 00:06:20,611
Not these had Christ in mind when he observed: ‘The seed fell upon good ground and yielded fruit an hundredfold,’ but these he meant when he declared: ‘The tree that beareth not fruit shall be cut down.

75
00:06:09,936 --> 00:06:17,736
All this time it has nothing to go by, it makes no pronouncement at all in the absence of experimental knowledge of the ground of truth.

76
00:06:17,736 --> 00:06:20,411
Intellect never rests in this life.

77
00:06:20,411 --> 00:06:25,311
However much God shows himself in this life it is nothing to what he really is.

78
00:06:20,611 --> 00:06:25,736
Thou mayst object: ‘But, Sir, what of that silence you said so much about?

79
00:06:25,311 --> 00:06:29,786
Truth lies in the ground, but veiled and concealed from the intellect.

80
00:06:25,736 --> 00:06:27,861
This means images galore.

81
00:06:27,861 --> 00:06:38,548
Every one of these acts has its appropriate image, be the act internal or external; whether it be teaching one or comforting another or arranging this or that, so what quiet can I get withal?

82
00:06:29,786 --> 00:06:34,511
And meantime the mind has no support to rest on as on something permanent.

83
00:06:34,511 --> 00:06:40,936
It gets no rest at all, but goes on expecting and preparing for something still to come but so far hidden.

84
00:06:38,548 --> 00:06:45,598
If the mind sees and formulates and the will wills and memory holds it fast, does not all this necessitate ideas?

85
00:06:40,936 --> 00:06:43,198
There is no knowing what God is.

86
00:06:43,198 --> 00:06:46,673
Something we do know, namely, what God is not.

87
00:06:45,598 --> 00:06:47,148
Let me explain.

88
00:06:46,673 --> 00:06:49,236
This the discerning soul rejects.

89
00:06:47,148 --> 00:06:51,548
We were speaking just now of the active intellect and the passive intellect.

90
00:06:49,236 --> 00:06:56,348
Intellect, meantime, finding no satisfaction in any mortal thing, is waiting, as matter awaits form.

91
00:06:56,348 --> 00:07:03,586
As matter is insatiable for form, so is intellect unsatisfied except with the essential, all-embracing truth.

92
00:07:03,586 --> 00:07:18,311
Only the truth will do, and this God keeps withdrawing from it step by step, purposing to arouse its zeal and lure it on to seek and grasp the actual causeless good: that, not content with any mortal thing, she may clamour more and more for the highest good of all.

93
00:07:18,311 --> 00:07:32,061
But thou wilt say: ‘Alas, Sir, you laid so much stress on our quieting our faculties and now this calm resolves itself into yearning and lamenting: to a muckle moan and clamour for something not possessed, which puts an end to peace and quiet.

94
00:07:32,061 --> 00:07:40,048
This may be desire or purpose or praise or thanksgiving or any of their brood, but it is not perfect peace and absolute stillness.

95
00:07:40,204 --> 00:08:04,891
I answer that, when thou hast emptied thyself entirely of thine own self and all things and of every sort of selfishness and hast transferred, united and abandoned thyself to God in perfect faith and complete amity, then everything that is born in thee or that enters into thee, external or internal, joyful or sorrowful, sour or sweet, is no longer thine own at all, but is altogether thy God’s to whom thou hast abandoned thyself.

96
00:08:04,891 --> 00:08:07,491
Tell me, whose is the spoken word?

97
00:08:07,491 --> 00:08:10,216
His who speaks it or his who hears it?

98
00:08:10,216 --> 00:08:15,416
Though it fall to the hearer it really belongs to the speaker, to him who gives it birth.

99
00:08:15,416 --> 00:08:22,016
The sun, for example, throws out light into the air and the air receives the light and transmits it to the earth.

100
00:08:22,016 --> 00:08:34,291
Now, although the light seems in the air, it is really in the sun: the light is actually from the sun, originating in the sun, not in the air: the air entertains it and passes it on to anything that can be lighted up.

101
00:08:34,291 --> 00:08:36,004
And so with the soul.

102
00:08:36,004 --> 00:08:50,991
God begets in the soul his child, his Word, and the soul conceiving it passes it on to her powers in varied guise, now as desire, now as good intent, now as charity, now as gratitude, or as it may take thee: It is his, not thine at all.

103
00:08:50,991 --> 00:08:59,054
What is thus wrought by God take thou as his and not thine own, as it is written, ‘The Holy Ghost asketh in us with unutterable yearnings.

104
00:08:59,054 --> 00:09:01,929
He prays in us, not we ourselves.

105
00:09:01,929 --> 00:09:08,116
St Paul says, ‘No one is able to say, Lord Jesus Christ, except in the Holy Ghost.

106
00:09:08,116 --> 00:09:10,966
Above all, lay no claim to anything.

107
00:09:10,966 --> 00:09:15,316
Let go thyself and let God act for thee and in thee as he pleases.

108
00:09:15,316 --> 00:09:20,891
This work is his, this Word is his, this birth is his and all thou art to boot.

109
00:09:20,891 --> 00:09:26,291
For thou hast abandoned thyself and art gone out of thy faculties and thy personal nature.

110
00:09:26,291 --> 00:09:35,966
God installs himself in thy nature and powers when, self-bereft of all belongings, thou dost take to the desert, as it is written, ‘A voice crying in the wilderness.

111
00:09:35,966 --> 00:09:42,741
Let this eternal voice cry on in thee at its sweet will and do thou be a desert in respect of self and creatures.

112
00:09:42,741 --> 00:09:49,479
Maybe thou wilt say: ‘But, Sir, what must one do to become this desert, void of self and creatures?

113
00:09:49,479 --> 00:10:00,091
Should one stay waiting for God all the time and do nothing oneself or should one do something between whiles, such as praying or reading or some good occupation like going to church or studying the Bible?

114
00:10:00,091 --> 00:10:06,354
Not, of course, taking things in from without, but everything from within, from one’s God.

115
00:10:06,354 --> 00:10:10,704
Besides, is there not something we miss by neglecting these things?

116
00:10:10,704 --> 00:10:34,529
My answer is this: Outward works were instituted and appointed for the purpose of directing the outer man to God and training him to ghostly life and virtues lest haply he should stray out of himself into ineptitudes: to act as a curb upon his inclination to run away from self to things abroad; so that when God shall choose to work in him he shall find him close at hand and not first have to fetch him back from things gross and alien.

117
00:10:34,529 --> 00:10:42,541
The greater is the pleasure in external things the harder work it is to leave them; the stronger the love the sharper the pain when it comes to parting.

118
00:10:42,700 --> 00:10:53,875
All pious practices—praying, reading, singing, watching, fasting, penance, or whatever discipline it be—were contrived to catch and keep us from things alien and ungodly.

119
00:10:53,825 --> 00:11:21,400
Suppose one feels God’s spirit is not working in one, but rather that one’s inner man is God-forsaken, that is the proper moment for the outward man to exercise the practical virtues, and particularly such as are most feasible and useful to him; not for his own selfish ends, but that, respect for truth preserving him from being led away by what is gross, he may stick straitly to God who will not need to seek him far afield, but will find him there at hand when he chooses to return and carry on

120
00:11:21,400 --> 00:11:23,400
his own work in his soul.

121
00:11:23,400 --> 00:11:35,337
But given that a man has genuine experience of the interior life, then let him boldly drop all outward disciplines, even those practices which thou art vowed to and from which neither pope nor prelate can release thee.

122
00:11:35,337 --> 00:11:41,425
From vows made to God no man can excuse thee: such vows are a bond between thyself and God.

123
00:11:41,425 --> 00:11:54,687
But supposing one has taken solemn vows of fasting, say, or prayer or pilgrimage, then on entering some order, one is released from them forthwith: in the order, obligation is to goodness as a whole, to God himself.

124
00:11:54,687 --> 00:11:56,312
And so I say here.

125
00:11:56,312 --> 00:12:02,662
Whatever one’s vows to manifold things, initiation into the real interior life releases from them.

126
00:12:02,662 --> 00:12:12,525
While the interior experience lasts, maybe a week, a month, a year, no hours are neglected by the monk or nun, for God who occupies them will also answer for them.

127
00:12:12,525 --> 00:12:22,200
On returning to himself the religious shall perform his vows for the time present, but the time elapsed and lost, as thou dost think, ’tis no business of thine to make good.

128
00:12:22,200 --> 00:12:24,950
God makes good any time he takes up.

129
00:12:24,950 --> 00:12:32,187
Think not to make it good by any act of creature, for the smallest act of God outweighs all the work of creatures put together.

130
00:12:32,187 --> 00:12:38,212
I am speaking here of clerks and those enlightened souls who are illumined by God and by the scriptures.

131
00:12:38,212 --> 00:12:45,562
But what about the poor profane who, ignorant of corporal discipline, has assumed some vow or other, praying or the like?

132
00:12:45,562 --> 00:12:47,262
My view is this.

133
00:12:47,262 --> 00:12:56,612
If he finds it hampering and that he draws much higher God and much more easily without it, let him boldly give it up, for whatever brings nearest to God is the best.

134
00:12:56,612 --> 00:13:03,225
Paul implied this when he said: ‘But when that which is perfect is come, that which is in part shall be done away.

135
00:13:03,225 --> 00:13:12,537
Vows taken before priests, vows of marriage, for example, are very different from these other obligations which amount to solemn promises of oneself to God.

136
00:13:12,537 --> 00:13:18,437
Vows taken with the laudable intention of binding oneself to God are for the moment the best way.

137
00:13:18,437 --> 00:13:25,825
But supposing that we find a better way, a way we feel and know to be much better, then the first may be deemed null and void.

138
00:13:25,825 --> 00:13:32,187
[[This is easy to prove, for we must look to the fruits, the inward truth, rather than to outward works.

139
00:13:32,187 --> 00:13:41,312
As St. Paul says: “The letter killeth (that is, all formal practices) but the spirit maketh alive (that is, inner experience of the truth).

140
00:13:41,312 --> 00:13:47,775
Realize this clearly, that whatever leads you closest to this inner truth, you are to follow in all you do.

141
00:13:47,775 --> 00:13:54,062
Let your spirit be uplifted and not downcast, burning and yet pure, silent and quiet.

142
00:13:54,062 --> 00:13:58,962
You need not say to God what you need or desire, for he knows it all beforehand.

143
00:13:58,962 --> 00:14:07,725
Christ said to his disciples: “When ye pray, use not vain repetitions as the heathen do: for they think that they shall be heard for their much speaking.]]

144
00:14:07,725 --> 00:14:19,175
[[That we may follow this peace and inward silence, that the eternal word may be spoken in us and understood, and that we may be one with him, may the Father help us, and the Word, and the spirit of both.

145
00:14:19,175 --> 00:14:20,112
Amen.]]

146
00:14:20,112 --> 00:14:30,462
Note: The last portion of this sermon (marked by double brackets) does not appear in Evans (1924), so it is excerpted from Blakney (1941).
